<p class="vt">
Broadcom is the <strong>single best risk-adjusted play on the AI infrastructure buildout</strong>. At 23x forward earnings with a 0.57 PEG ratio, it's the cheapest mega-cap AI exposure available — cheaper than NVDA, MSFT, or GOOGL on a growth-adjusted basis. <strong>AI revenue is accelerating</strong> (not decelerating): +106% in Q1, guided +140% in Q2, with CEO line-of-sight to $100B by FY2027. The 77% gross margin, 68% EBITDA margin, and $8B quarterly FCF make it a compounding machine. The Google and Anthropic long-term supply deals provide multi-year visibility.
<br><br>
<strong>Position: 5–7% core holding.</strong> Entry zone $290–325 is attractive. The TSMC bottleneck is the primary near-term risk — if supply constrains execution, the $100B FY27 target may slip. But Broadcom's custom ASIC moat (XPUs, networking, SerDes) makes it irreplaceable to its 6 hyperscaler customers. The Jun 11 Q2 earnings will validate or challenge the $22B guidance. Infrastructure software flatness is a secondary concern but manageable given the AI revenue surge. This is the rare stock where both growth investors and value investors can agree.
